{{about|the sequence 1, 5, 9, 13, ...|<math>2^{\sqrt{2}}</math>|Gelfond–Schneider constant}}
In [[number theory]], a branch of [[mathematics]], a '''Hilbert number''' is a [[positive integer]] of the form {{math|4''n'' + 1}} ({{harvtxt|Flannery|Flannery|2000|p=35}}). The Hilbert numbers were named after [[David Hilbert]].

The sequence of Hilbert numbers begins 1, 5, 9, 13, 17, ... {{OEIS|id=A016813}}).  A '''Hilbert prime''' is a Hilbert number that is not divisible by a smaller Hilbert number (other than 1). The sequence of Hilbert primes begins

:5, 9, 13, 17, 21, 29, 33, 37, 41, 49, ... {{OEIS|id=A057948}}.

A Hilbert prime is not necessarily a [[prime number]]; for example, 21 is a [[composite number]] since {{math|1=21 = 3 &sdot; 7}}.  However, 21 {{em|is}} a Hilbert prime since neither 3 nor 7 (the only factors of 21 other than 1 and itself) are Hilbert numbers.  It follows from multiplication [[modular arithmetic|modulo]] 4 that a Hilbert prime is either a prime number of the form {{math|4''n'' + 1}} (called a [[Pythagorean prime]]), or a [[semiprime]] of the form {{math|(4''a'' + 3) &sdot; (4''b'' + 3)}}.

